node.text: NASA astronauts Shane Kimbrough and Megan McArthur, Akihiko Hoshide of JAXA, and Thomas Pesquet of ESA get together to answer your questions about life in space, astronaut training, and their upcoming mission launching next month.

node.title: Get to know the astronauts of NASA’s SpaceX Crew-2 mission!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Johnson Space Center on July 20, 2021. May be an image of standing and text.

node.text:
TWO spacewalk anniversaries today! 👩‍🚀

This #NationalMoonDay, it’s the 52nd anniversary of “one giant leap for mankind.” It was the day Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin took the first spacewalk on the Moon! 🌖

Exactly 20 years later in 2001, @nasaastronauts Michael Gernhardt and James Reilly took the first spacewalk out of the Quest Joint Airlock. The two had installed it to the @iss days prior.

node.text:
The astronauts of NASA’s @spacex Crew-3 mission. 

Raja Chari (@astro_raja) will serve as mission commander with Tom Marshburn as pilot. Both are @nasaastronauts. 

Matthias Maurer of the European Space Agency and Kayla Barron of NASA will serve as mission specialists for the mission. 

The four are scheduled to launch no earlier than Oct. 31 from @nasakennedy, and will arrive at the @iss shortly after.

node.text:
The final flight.

10 years ago today in NASA history, the space shuttle Atlantis launched four @nasaastronauts to the International Space Station (@ISS).

The 12-day STS-135 mission brought an end to the 30-year space shuttle program. Atlantis' flight was the last time a space shuttle would launch. 

"When a generation accomplishes a great thing, it's got a right to stand back and for just a moment admire and take pride in its work," said astronaut Christopher Ferguson. "As the ISS now enters the era of utilization, we'll never forget the role the space shuttle played in its creation. Like a proud parent, we anticipate great things to follow from the men and women who build, operate, and live there."

node.text:
The first sample of an asteroid called Ryugu has arrived!

NASA's Johnson Space Center in Houston received its first sample of asteroid Ryugu, which was returned to Earth last December by the Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency’s (JAXA) Hayabusa2 spacecraft.

Studying carbonaceous asteroids like Ryugu could help scientists better understand how the solar system formed.

This is one of the first samples to leave Japan for preliminary investigation. As deputy leader of the mineralogy-petrology subteam for the preliminary analysis effort, Mike Zolensky was one of the first scientists to examine the sample to determine its basic nature.

Alongside Zolensky, Jangmi Han from the Astromaterials Research and Exploration Science Division, and James Martinez of the Structural Engineering Division at NASA Johnson worked together to complete an investigation of the sample.

Sample analyses were performed in the Scanning Electron Microscopy Lab in Johnson’s Structural Engineering Division within five days. Zolensky is one of a hundred investigators worldwide to receive a sample from JAXA.

node.text:
#SpotTheSpacewalker. That pair of legs you see against the background of Earth belongs to NASA astronaut Shane Kimbrough! (@astro_kimbrough)

Kimbrough conducted a spacewalk with ESA astronaut Thomas Pesquet to install new roll-out solar panels to the @iss.

This was the view from the Mission Control Center in Houston 1 hour and 34 minutes into the spacewalk. The spacewalkers spent more than 6 hours in total outside of the space station on Friday. 

📸: NASA / Robert Markowitz

node.text:
Happy #nationalselfieday from the Expedition 65 crew aboard the @ISS! 

Thomas Pesquet took the first photo last week during the first spacewalk to install new solar arrays to the International Space Station.

Mark Vande Hei snapped the second photo during his 2018 mission. He was doing maintenance on the station's robotic arm.

Aki Hoshide of Japan took his space selfie back in 2012 before installing a camera onto Canadarm2 outside of the space station.

Thomas got astronauts Shane Kimbrough and Aki Hoshide in the frame while the trio were in the @SpaceX Crew Dragon vehicle named Endeavour.

Megan McArthur and Aki Hoshide pause for a selfie in the fourth photo while their crewmates participated in a downlink event.

Megan also took a cool selfie with her reflection shown in a floating water bubble in 2009 in the final photo.

@thom_astro @astro_kimbrough @astro.megan #selfie #space #spacestation

node.text:
What do you want to name the manikin launching to the Moon on NASA’s #Artemis I mission?

Before NASA launches with a human crew of astronauts, we’re sending a “Moonikin” mass simulator for the first launch. And we need your help choosing it’s name!

This bracket-style contest is now open! The choices are: ACE, Wargo, Delos, Duhart, Campos, Shackleton, Montgomery, and Rigel.

Check out our link in bio for the meaning behind the names and how you can vote for your favorite!

node.text:
New solar arrays are seen inside a @spacex Cargo Dragon spacecraft shortly after launching to the @iss.

These roll-out solar arrays are now on the space station, and two upcoming spacewalks are planned to install them. Today, the crew in orbit is unpacking the solar arrays from Dragon in preparation for the spacewalks. 

Live coverage of the installation begins at 6:30 a.m EDT on both June 16 and June 20.  Follow along live on NASA TV!

node.text:
NASA astronaut Kate Rubins adjusts research hardware aboard the International Space Station (@ISS). Her feet are strapped to the floor to give her leverage as she works in the station’s low gravity. This low gravity poses a unique risk: For every month in space, astronauts’ weight-bearing bones become roughly 1% less dense if they don’t take precautions to counter this loss.

Without the continuous load of Earth’s gravity, bone tissues reshape themselves. Cells that build new bone slow down their work and cells that remove old bone keep chugging along. Removal outpaces growth, producing weaker, more brittle bones. Simultaneously, muscles usually activated by simply standing on Earth start to atrophy because they no longer need to work as hard.

To learn more, NASA turns to researchers like Dr. Ashley Weaver, a biomedical engineer in the Center for Injury Biomechanics at Wake Forest University in Winston-Salem, North Carolina. Weaver and her team study how spaceflight affects the network of bones and muscles in the spinal column.

The team compares detailed scans of astronauts’ spines immediately before and after spaceflight. Changes in the scans reveal the degree to which spaceflight hollows out bones. They also reveal how much spaceflight causes muscles to atrophy, seen through the accumulation of fat tissue and shifts in muscle size.

Trends found will help scientists and engineers to brainstorm strategies — such as specific resistive exercises — to counter bone and muscle loss in space. On Earth, similar strategies could help people with bone diseases such as osteoporosis to strengthen their weakened spines.

Expedition 64 crew were among the last examined for this study. "Now that all scanning is complete, we're looking forward to learning what bone and muscle changes occur during space missions and how these relate to injury risk," explains Weaver.

node.text:
Science and new roll-out solar arrays are making their way to the @ISS!

SpaceX's 22nd commercial resupply mission launched from @NASAKennedy earlier today, carrying 7,300 pounds of cargo to the astroanuts orbiting the Earth aboard the International Space Station.

Expedition 65 flight controllers monitored the launch from the Mission Control Center in Houston under the direction of flight director Rebecca Wingfield. The cargo is expected to arrive at the space station around 5 a.m. Saturday, June 5.

node.text:
Mizuna mustard greens grow on the International Space Station (@ISS) inside its Vegetable Production System, also known as Veggie. Here on Earth, pandemic-induced isolation has led people to take up baking or gardening. Could developing a space-faring green thumb also help astronauts ease their sense of confinement and isolation?

NASA’s Human Research Program has given Gioia Massa, a scientist at NASA's Kennedy Space Center (@NASAKennedy), the task of finding out. To learn more, Massa and her team are asking astronauts who currently cultivate vegetables on the station to each complete a survey about their space-gardening experiences. For example, crew members who grow mizuna mustards take the survey two to three times over the plant’s month-long growth cycle.

Questions on the survey help gauge how space-gardening affects astronauts’ moods. For example: Was gardening engaging, demanding, or meaningful? Did it impact the passage of time, performance of mission tasks, or relationships with crew members? Did gardening enhance their connection to Earth, desire to harvest or consume the plants, or food consumption in general? How effective was gardening as a source of sensory stimulation for sight, touch, smell, and taste?

When the vegetables are ready to eat, the astronauts also rate the flavor, color, appearance, aroma, texture, and taste of the produce. This allows researchers to assess whether the labor over veggies proved fruitful as a supplement to prepackaged space food.

Thus far, seven astronauts have completed the survey. Massa hopes to survey a total of 24 astronauts before the study is complete. Initial results show that some participants loved working with and caring for the plants, while others preferred different activities. Despite the variability, no one viewed their work with the plants as meaningless, and all valued the utility of growing plants in space. Astronauts’ feedback will help NASA better design food systems for future space missions.

node.text:
John "Blue Flight" Hodge. 1929 - 2021.

Hodge served as one of @nasaflightdirectors, the second person to hold this role in agency history.

As flight director, he oversaw the final solo flight of the Mercury Program, Mercury-Atlas 9, in which astronaut Gordon Cooper flew his Faith 7 spacecraft for 22 orbits of the Earth, setting the stage for the two-person crews of Gemini and the three-person crews of Apollo.

Throughout his career Hodge continued to lead teams through major milestones in NASA's spaceflight history both in and out of the Mission Control Center in Houston.

He’ll always be a part of our storied history at NASA’s Johnson Space Center, and our hearts go out to his family during this difficult time.
